2) 
✅ Definition

“In Apache Spark, Parquet is preferred because it is a columnar storage format that provides efficient data compression, faster query performance, and supports optimizations like predicate pushdown.”

🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 You have a dataset with 50 columns

Query needs only 2 columns
CSV:
Reads all 50 columns ❌
Parquet:
Reads only 2 columns ✔
⚙️ Key Advantages
🔹 1. Columnar Storage

👉 Reads only required columns → less I/O

🔹 2. Compression

👉 Stores data efficiently → less storage

🔹 3. Predicate Pushdown

👉 Filters applied at data source → faster

🔹 4. Schema Support

👉 No need to infer → faster + consistent

🔹 5. Better Performance

👉 Optimized for analytics queries

💻 Example
df.write.parquet("data.parquet")

df = spark.read.parquet("data.parquet")
🎤 Interview Answer

👉
“Parquet is preferred because its columnar format reduces I/O by reading only required columns, supports compression, and enables optimizations like predicate pushdown, resulting in significantly better performance compared to row-based formats

3) Schema evolution allows Spark to handle changes in data structure over time, such as adding or modifying columns, without breaking existing pipelines, especially when using formats like Parquet or ORC.

4 ) 🔹 Partitioned Data
✅ Definition
“In Apache Spark, partitioned data refers to storing data physically divided into separate folders based on column values, allowing Spark to read only relevant partitions during queries.”

💻 Example
df.write.partitionBy("year").parquet("data/")
👉 Directory structure:
data/ ├── year=2023/ ├── year=2024/

=====================================================

5 ) 🔹 Small File Problem
✅ Definition

“In Apache Spark, the small file problem occurs when data is stored in a large number of tiny files, causing excessive overhead in metadata handling, task scheduling, and I/O operations, which degrades performance.”

🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 Instead of:

10 files × 100MB  ✔

You have:

10,000 files × 100KB  ❌

👉 Spark:

Creates 1 task per file
Too many tasks → overhead
Slow job

6) 1. Coalesce (Best for reducing files)
df.coalesce(10).write.parquet("data/")

👉 Reduces number of partitions without full shuffle ✔

🔹 2. Repartition (for balanced distribution)
df.repartition(10).write.parquet("data/")

👉 Uses shuffle → better distribution ✔

🔹 3. Control partitions before write

👉 Avoid:

df.repartition(1000)  # ❌ creates many small files

👉 Use:

df.repartition(10)
🔹 4. Optimize partitioning column

👉 Avoid high-cardinality columns
👉 Use:

date ✔
region ✔
🔹 5. File Compaction (Advanced)

👉 Merge existing small files:

df = spark.read.parquet("data/")
df.coalesce(10).write.mode("overwrite").parquet("data/")
🔹 6. Tune shuffle partitions
spark.conf.set("spark.sql.shuffle.partitions", "50")

👉 Prevents excessive small files

