7 ) ✅ Definition

“In Apache Spark, compression is the process of reducing the size of data by encoding it efficiently, which helps save storage space and improve read/write performance.”

Compression reduces data size, improving storage efficiency and performance by minimizing disk I/O and network transfer

💻 Example
# Write with compression
df.write.option("compression", "snappy").parquet("data/")
🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 Without compression:

100GB data ❌

👉 With compression:

30GB data ✔

👉 Benefits:

Less disk usage ✔

8 ) 

🔹 Snappy Compression
✅ Definition

“Snappy compression is a fast compression algorithm used in Apache Spark that prioritizes speed over maximum compression, making it ideal for big data processing.”

💻 Example
df.write.option("compression", "snappy").parquet("data/")
🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 You have 100GB data

Gzip → reduces to ~20GB (slow)
Snappy → reduces to ~30–40GB (fast) ✔

👉 In Spark:

Faster read/write ✔
Less CPU usage ✔
⚙️ Key Insight

👉
Snappy = moderate compression + very fast speed

⚡ Why Spark uses Snappy by default
Faster processing
Good enough compression
Balanced performance
🎤 Interview Answer

👉
“Snappy is a fast compression algorithm used in Spark that provides a balance between compression ratio and speed, making it suitable for large-scale data processing.”

9 ) 🔹 How Spark Reads Files
✅ Definition

“In Apache Spark, Spark reads files by splitting them into partitions and processing those partitions in parallel across executors.”

💻 Example
df = spark.read.parquet("data/")
df.show()
🧠 Simple Scenario

👉 You have a 1GB file

Spark splits it into chunks (say 10 partitions)
Each executor processes one chunk

👉 Result:

Parallel processing ✔
Faster execution ✔
⚙️ Step-by-Step Flow
Read File
   ↓
Split into partitions
   ↓
Assign to executors
   ↓
Process in parallel
⚡ What affects reading performance
File format (Parquet faster than CSV)
Number of partitions
File size (avoid small files)
Predicate pushdown
🎤 Interview Answer

👉
“Spark reads files by dividing them into partitions and processing them in parallel across executors, which enables scalable and efficient data processing.”

10 ) 🔹 Metadata in Parquet
✅ Definition

“In Apache Spark, metadata in Parquet refers to information stored alongside the data, such as schema, column types, and statistics, which helps Spark read and query data efficiently without scanning the entire file.”

💻 Example (concept)
df = spark.read.parquet("data/")
df.printSchema()

👉 Schema is read from metadata, not inferred ✔

